**Decision Tree Model**
*1. Select Predictors*

We selected duration, poutcome, campaign, housing, month, balance, age, and contact because these variables showed significant effects in our Task 2 regression models—particularly duration and poutcome, which were the strongest predictors of campaign-related outcomes.

*2. Fit the Decision Tree*

```{r}
tree_model <- rpart(y ~ duration + poutcome + campaign + housing + month + balance + age + contact, data = train, method = "class", control = rpart.control(cp = 0.01))

print(tree_model)
summary(tree_model)
```

*3. Generate Predicted Probablities (Test Set)*

Get predicted probablities for class "yes"
```{r}
tree_prob <- predict(tree_model, newdata = test, type = "prob")[, "yes"]

head(tree_prob)
```

*4. Plot the Decision Tree*

basic plot
```{r}
plot(tree_model, uniform = TRUE, main = "Decision Tree for Term Deposit Subscription")
text(tree_model, use.n = TRUE, all = TRUE, cex = 0.7)
```

nicer visualization
```{r}
library(rpart.plot)
rpart.plot(tree_model,
           type = 4, #label all nodes
           extra = 104, #show probability and percent of observations
           fallen.leaves = TRUE,
           main = "Decision Tree: Term Deposit Subscription")
```
*5. Evaluate at three thresholds*
We evaluate the Decision Tree model at three cutoff thresholds (0.3, 0.5, 0.7) using confusion matrices and accuracy rates.

```{r}
evaluate_cutoff <- function(probs, actual, threshold = 0.5, model_name = "Model") {
  pred <- ifelse(probs > threshold, "yes", "no")
  confusion <- table(Predicted = pred, Actual = actual)
  TP <- sum(pred == "yes" & actual == "yes")
  TN <- sum(pred == "no" & actual == "no")
  FP <- sum(pred == "yes" & actual == "no")
  FN <- sum(pred == "no" & actual == "yes")
  accuracy <- (TP + TN) / (TP + TN + FP + FN)
  cat(paste0(" ", model_name, " @ cutoff = ", threshold, "\n"))
  print(confusion)
  cat(sprintf("Accuracy: %.3f\n\n", accuracy))
}

# Run at all three thresholds
evaluate_cutoff(tree_prob, test$y, threshold = 0.3, model_name = "Decision Tree")
evaluate_cutoff(tree_prob, test$y, threshold = 0.5, model_name = "Decision Tree")
evaluate_cutoff(tree_prob, test$y, threshold = 0.7, model_name = "Decision Tree")
```
At a threshold of 0.3, the model is more aggressive in predicting "yes," capturing more potential subscribers but also producing more false positives.
At a threshold of 0.5, the model uses the standard cutoff, balancing between catching subscribers and avoiding false alarms.
At a threshold of 0.7, the model is more conservative, only predicting "yes" when highly confident, which reduces false positives but may miss real subscribers.

Based on the accuracy rates across all three thresholds, we selected threshold = 0.5 because it produced the highest accuracy of 88.9%.
